This is a 50 ft long piece of strong rope, useful in a number of situations.
A comfortable bed large enough to accommodate two medium-sized creatures.
A fine rendition of a ship sailing upon a stormy sea.
A tapestry telling an old tale of an ancient tragedy... how love was found, and how it was lost as well.
This tapestry has a beautiful seacape picture shown upon it. It depicts a lighthouse at sunset looking over a beautiful harbor.
This tapestry shows a peacefull forest scene with a few wild deer looking about as they drink from a stream.
A very rare black pearl, and the cut on this specimen is perfect. This would make a stunning addition to any pirate's treasure trove.
The most valued amethyst crystals are a milky, wine-dark purple.
This amber gem is round cut, and of a slightly yellowish color.
One of the world's rarest and most coveted gems, alexandrite takes on a brilliant green hue when under indirect sunlight but turns blood-red when exposed to candlelight.
When cut and polished, aventurine is as alluring as its name. It resembles misty quartz, but contains glistening flecks of green that give it a unique sheen.
Bloodstone gems are a deep red color and often considered to hold some mystic properties, though usually associated with black magic.
This smallish but well cut stone has a handsome bluish tone when held to the light.
This is a large rough hewn onyx crystal. Gemstones of this type are known to be prized by the more infamous pirate captains, probably due to the crystal's dark and imposing color.
These semi-precious stones are usually some shade of green. This particular specimen is quite unspectacular though.
The Pink Pearl is a white pearl with the hint of rose coloring to it.
A small red ruby, but of a beautifully rich coloration, exquisitely cut.
A brilliant little emerald cut stone of yellowish-brown color, this would make a fine noble's ring, if set properly.
Tourmaline is a wonderful gemstone. It comes in almost every color in the rainbow and is one the brightest and most versatile gemstones that can be found.
This uncut tourmaline has potential, if cut by the proper hand. Even as it is, it could still be worth something.
